### Generate Turbopack Trace Files for Debugging

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/08-turbopack.mdx

To diagnose performance or memory issues with Turbopack in Next.js, run the development server with the `NEXT_TURBOPACK_TRACING=1` environment variable. This command generates a `.next/dev/trace-turbopack` file for investigation.

```bash
NEXT_TURBOPACK_TRACING=1 next dev
```

--------------------------------

### Enable Debug IDs in Turbopack JavaScript Bundles

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Configure Turbopack to generate debug IDs in JavaScript bundles and source maps according to the ECMA-426 proposal. The debugIds option automatically adds a polyfill for compatibility and exposes debug IDs via the globalThis._debugIds global variable.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    debugIds: true,
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Turbopack Options in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/08-turbopack.mdx

This JavaScript example demonstrates how to configure Turbopack within `next.config.js`. It shows setting up a `resolveAlias` for module aliasing and extending `resolveExtensions` to include additional file types for resolution.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    // Example: adding an alias and custom file extension
    resolveAlias: {
      underscore: 'lodash',
    },
    resolveExtensions: ['.mdx', '.tsx', '.ts', '.jsx', '.js', '.json'],
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Manually Configure Turbopack Root Directory in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

This snippet demonstrates how to manually set the `root` option for Turbopack in `next.config.js`. This is useful when Next.js cannot automatically detect the project root or when working with linked dependencies, allowing resolution of modules outside the default project scope.

```js
const path = require('path')
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    root: path.join(__dirname, '..'),
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Enable Turbopack FileSystem Caching in Next.config

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopackFileSystemCache.mdx

Configure Turbopack FileSystem Cache in Next.js by setting experimental flags for both development and production builds. This enables Turbopack to persist build data to the .next folder, improving performance across multiple builds. The feature is stable for development and experimental for production use.

```typescript
import type { NextConfig } from 'next'

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  experimental: {
    // Enable filesystem caching for `next dev`
    turbopackFileSystemCacheForDev: true,
    // Enable filesystem caching for `next build`
    turbopackFileSystemCacheForBuild: true,
  },
}

export default nextConfig
```

```javascript
/** @type {import('next').NextConfig} */
const nextConfig = {
  experimental: {
    // Enable filesystem caching for `next dev`
    turbopackFileSystemCacheForDev: true,
    // Enable filesystem caching for `next build`
    turbopackFileSystemCacheForBuild: true,
  },
}

module.exports = nextConfig
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Turbopack Alias for Legacy Sass Tilde Imports (JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/08-turbopack.mdx

This JavaScript snippet for 'next.config.js' shows how to configure a 'turbopack.resolveAlias' to map the legacy tilde (~) syntax to standard paths. This configuration allows projects using Webpack's ~ syntax for node_modules Sass imports to function correctly with Turbopack without requiring changes to existing SCSS files.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveAlias: {
      '~*': '*'
    }
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Custom File Extensions Resolution in Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Set custom module resolution extensions using the resolveExtensions field in next.config.js. This overwrites the default extension list, so include all required extensions. The example includes common extensions for TypeScript, JSX, JavaScript, and JSON files.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveExtensions: ['.mdx', '.tsx', '.ts', '.jsx', '.js', '.mjs', '.json'],
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Install latest Next.js and run dev with Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/local-development.mdx

Update Next.js to the latest version to access performance improvements and use Turbopack as the default bundler for development. Turbopack provides significant performance benefits over webpack for local development.

```bash
npm install next@latest
npm run dev  # Turbopack is used by default
```

--------------------------------

### Migrate Sass node_modules Imports for Next.js Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/upgrading/version-16.mdx

Illustrates the change in Sass import syntax for `node_modules` between Webpack and Turbopack. Webpack supported the legacy tilde (`~`) prefix, while Turbopack requires direct path imports. This snippet shows how to update `@import` statements for compatibility with Turbopack.

```scss
@import '~bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css';
```

```scss
@import 'bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css';
```

--------------------------------

### Define Turbopack options in Next.js configuration (TypeScript/JavaScript)

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

This code snippet shows how to configure Turbopack-specific options within your Next.js configuration file, `next.config.ts` or `next.config.js`. The `turbopack` object allows for customization of file transformation and module resolution, accepting properties like `root`, `rules`, `resolveAlias`, and `resolveExtensions`.

```ts
import type { NextConfig } from 'next'

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  turbopack: {
    // ...
  },
}

export default nextConfig
```

```js
/** @type {import('next').NextConfig} */
const nextConfig = {
  turbopack: {
    // ...
  },
}

module.exports = nextConfig
```

