### Next.js Turbopack CSS Module Import Order (JSX)

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/08-turbopack.mdx

This JSX snippet illustrates how Turbopack prioritizes CSS module imports within a React component. It ensures that 'utils.module.css' is loaded before 'button.module.css' by following the JavaScript import sequence, which can lead to different styling outcomes compared to Webpack's behavior in some edge cases.

```jsx
import utilStyles from './utils.module.css'
import buttonStyles from './button.module.css'
export default function BlogPost() {
  return (
    <div className={utilStyles.container}>
      <button className={buttonStyles.primary}>Click me</button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure SVGR Webpack Loader with Options in Next.js

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

This snippet demonstrates how to pass configuration options to a webpack loader within Turbopack rules in `next.config.js`. It extends the previous example by providing the `@svgr/webpack` loader with an `icon: true` option, allowing more granular control over the loader's behavior.

```js
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    rules: {
      '*.svg': {
        loaders: [
          {
            loader: '@svgr/webpack',
            options: {
              icon: true,
            },
          },
        ],
        as: '*.js',
      },
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Opt Out of Turbopack for Next.js Build using Webpack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/upgrading/version-16.mdx

This `package.json` script configuration allows you to opt out of Turbopack for the production build process by explicitly using the `--webpack` flag with `next build`. This is useful if you need to continue using Webpack for specific reasons while still leveraging Turbopack for development.

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "next dev",
    "build": "next build --webpack",
    "start": "next start"
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Module Resolution Aliases in Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/turbopack.mdx

Map imported module patterns to new destinations using resolveAlias in next.config.js. Supports simple string aliases and conditional aliasing for browser environments. In this example, 'underscore' imports are redirected to 'lodash', and 'mocha' imports use conditional aliasing based on the browser condition.

```javascript
module.exports = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveAlias: {
      underscore: 'lodash',
      mocha: { browser: 'mocha/browser-entry.js' },
    },
  },
}
```

--------------------------------

### Opt-in to Webpack bundler instead of Turbopack

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/local-development.mdx

Run Next.js development server with webpack bundler instead of the default Turbopack. Use this when you need to revert to webpack for compatibility or specific requirements.

```bash
npm run dev --webpack
```

