### Troubleshooting - HMR Cache and Development

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/04-functions/fetch.mdx

Information about fetch caching behavior during development, HMR (Hot Module Replacement) cache behavior, and how default caching options interact with fresh data display in development mode.

```APIDOC
## Troubleshooting - Fetch Caching in Development

### Issue
Default `auto` cache and `cache: 'no-store'` options not showing fresh data in development between HMR refreshes.

### Root Cause
Next.js caches fetch() responses in Server Components across Hot Module Replacement (HMR) in local development to:
- Provide faster responses
- Reduce costs for billed API calls

The HMR cache applies to all fetch requests, including those with:
- Default `auto` cache option
- Explicit `cache: 'no-store'` option

### Behavior
- **During HMR Refresh**: Cached responses are reused between HMR updates. Uncached requests will not show fresh data from previous HMR refreshes.
- **On Navigation**: HMR cache is cleared when navigating to a different page
- **On Full-Page Reload**: HMR cache is cleared on full-page refresh (F5, Cmd+R)

### Solution
Clear the HMR cache and enable fresh data fetching by:
- Performing a full-page reload (F5 or Cmd+R)
- Navigating to a different page, then back

Refer to [`serverComponentsHmrCache`](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/serverComponentsHmrCache) configuration for advanced cache control options.
```

